commentBody:
@Barry Ancona. I laughed out loud after a few minutes of struggling to understand 10d (Against the rules). NO TOK, what the heck is NO TOK? Then I was reminded of the crosswordese knowledge you recently shared on being DOOKed.  

Did others DO OK with 10d or did others feel NOT OK about the clueing to NO TOK?


My wife thinks it’s funny when I chuckle to myself while doing the puzzle.  Thanks to the puzzling community for providing humor to my day.

@Julia 
It makes sense if you think of them as false sightings. Something that looks like Nessie, but then turns out to be a log, might be a NESSEE.

All the theme entries end with something like "never mind," letting you know that the cryptid spotter may not be the most reliable witness.

@Calig 

It was done to torment us.

Emus like it.

@Apurv 

You are correct. 

But I am willing to cut Elie Levine a little slack. The Wordplay column is not her regular gig, and I’m pretty sure that she doesn’t have a COPY EDITOR.

@Eric Hougland 

I have a feeling Apurv is peeved by the lack of attention to detail when referencing India. I can sympathize given the commonly hit-and-miss references to Slavs (and the blunder with chai from a few months ago).




[Moderation evasion padding of emu feathers]

@El Jefe

Yeah, I do the same. On the first pass I skip the clues I don't instantly know the answer to. On Saturdays that may be all of them :D







[Skipping emus]

@UCCF 

I just noticed, perusing recent college football schools, the the University of Washington is now referred to as WAZZU. (Akin to Missouri’s MISSOU). 

!!!!

@Steve L 

the University of Washington is U DUB 

Washington State University is WAZZU

@NotMyRealName 
The point was that people who believe in these creatures want to see something that isn’t there. The cryptid names embedded in another clue are almost there, but not quite, to reflect this. 
I did like the previous poster’s idea of changing “cryptozoologist” to “crtypozoologist” though!

@Rusty Wheelhouse 

You are a wonderful additiion to the Commentariat!

I will pass this to DHubby to read, as my reading it aloud (as I often do with humorous comments) would temper the fun of seeing ths spellings!

@Rusty Wheelhouse 
Thank you for this wonderful post! The Dahu was completely new to me and I think I will look up the title you suggest. TIL the manner in which to capture one of these creatures:
“…to catch a dahu requires two people: one with a bag, and another who is good at imitating dahu sounds. The former stands at the bottom of the slope, and the other behind a dahu. When the dahu turns around to see the source of the sound, it will lose its balance and roll down the slope to the person with the bag.” (From the wiki entry). Priceless!

@Rusty Wheelhouse 

It happens all the time.  It's happened to all of us.

We always blame the emus, not the poster.

@Mean Old Lady 

I don’t remember Manny Nosowsky from my earlier puzzle-solving days (mid- to late-1990s; I guess life got in the way for a while). But I have come to greatly admire his skills through my visits to the archives. His puzzles rarely disappoint. 

I’ve tried more than once to find out if he’s still around. If he is, I don’t think he’s still constructing.

@Times Rita @Barry Ancona

I Said So was my first answer, too. No never occurred to me. 

Of course [Language suffix] would have solved the ambiguity. So too would have a geographical clue (X to Y direction). I like those because they’re mostly set in the lower 48, where my geography skills are strongest. And sometimes I learn something that contradicts my mental map, such as the fact that Reno is further west than LA.

@Craig 

Actually, it was Eye-gor. 

You’re missing out the fact that they were referring to the movie, Young Frankenstein, not the original novel.

@Matt 

They weren’t pointless. You just missed the point. (See all the parentheticals in the clues.)

For what it’s worth, I didn’t think this was the cleverest theme ever, but that doesn’t mean the misspellings were pointless.

@B 

Just got to the comments and yours is the first I'm reading.

Totally agree with you.

@B 

The DELI clue is pretty good. 

Perhaps it will make Lewis’s list next week, assuming things are closer to normal in Asheville then.

@A 
That is one of the few things that did not grate...quite a few acceptable spellings of that word, in my experience.
Since you lot put in U's that we do not, we can call this even.

@Pat 

When I worked for the Texas Legislature drafting legislation, we had legal editors whose jobs included copy editing. We also had proofreaders, whose main job was to make sure that the final document matched the marked-up draft sent to the document processing division. Those were very different jobs. 

Both groups saved me from making mistakes many times.

@B 

Where I worked, the proofreaders also looked for typos and similar errors. If there was no question about the correct word, the proofers could fix it. But if there was any doubt, they were supposed to check with the editor. 

I don’t envy those folks. Most of the proofers were employed only for the legislative session (five months or so). They worked long hours, late into the night.

@Lara 

Congratulations!

Stick with it! You’ll have no-lookup-Saturdays sooner than you think!

@Kelli 

Also, check your dictionary. What you’ll find might not align what they taught you in school. 

And besides, they’re just misspellings, since none of the gray areas spell real words.

@Tony Lovell 

Not sure why you've chosen today specifically to grace us with this knowledge, but thank you nonetheless. 

I'm still fairly new to crossword solving, but I have never felt the placement of a rebus to be "arbitrary," excepting the fact that the English language often is, broadly speaking. If I ever have to guess what to enter into a square, that's my own failure, not that of the puzzle/constructor.

@HeathieJ 

A bit convoluted for me. 

I solved easily enough, but couldn't figure out the trick, as opposed to th blood typos etc I recently encountered.

@Eric Hougland 

Scroll down in the Strands thread:

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/shared/comment/426n8c?rsrc=cshare&smid=url-share" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/shared/comment/426n8c?rsrc=cshare&smid=url-share</a>

@Andrzej 

Please consider Hardroch’s advice. I’ve done lots of urban biking, mostly in Texas, where few drivers are also cyclists. 

As I said, most of the ride around Manhattan is on a dedicated bike path. It’s a great way to see the city.

@Robert Kern 

“Because I SAY SO” is an in-the-language expression. “Because I SAY NO” is what they call “green paint”.  The complaining you’d have heard if they’d gone with the latter would have put the “misspelled cryptids” complaining to shame. 

(“Green paint” refers to words that make sense together but aren’t accepted set phrases.)

@Francis 

tl;dr version

If you offer an opinion about the puzzle, you have entered the realm of criticism.  Your critique is also open to criticism.

@Remy 

Funny how you come to that conclusion without knowing the song. There’s a reason it’s called “Shake It Off”!

(Funny how many people have an opinion of Taylor Swift without knowing anything about her.)

@Steve L

Didn’t you notice the “ “ around hate?  

I didn’t want to overuse emojis or exclamation points in my post to make it look lighthearted.

@J!m 

Exceptionally mean.

I hope you don't work on a suicide hotline.

@HeathieJ 

Yeah, he was kicked around pretty badly, and had I been younger I might have joined in.

Love you comment on children.  The most we should hope for from them is integrity and fairness, not a carbon copy of us.

@Erin 

Consider what it would have been if the word was said twice. Isn’t that “repeated once”?

The first time isn’t a repetition.

@HeathieJ 

My heart sinks a little every time there's a disturbingly vicious and trivial post.

Pointless denigration is something I really struggle with.  And there's so much of it everywhere.  You'd think we could rise above it in this tiny, insignificant corner of the world.

@HeathieJ 

Emus ate my reply.  Probably too many caps, as I was very excited that I knew your link was going to be for the "jerk store".  I guess emus are terrified of exuberance.

That was just quintessential Seinfeld/David.  Working so hard to overcome that "I shoulda said..." feeling, only to be knocked down again.

@Francis 

